<p class=""><h2>Key Challenges in the Nuts Huller Market</h2><ul>    <li>        <strong>High Initial Investment:</strong>        The nuts huller industry requires substantial capital for purchasing advanced machinery and equipment. This poses a threat to small-scale processors who might struggle to secure financing.    </li>    <li>        <strong>Labor Shortages:</strong>        Many regions are experiencing a shortage of skilled laborers, which affects productivity and hulling efficiency. Automation can mitigate this but comes with a high cost and operational complexity.    </li>    <li>        <strong>Quality Control:</strong>        Maintaining consistent quality during the hulling process is challenging. Poorly hulled nuts can lead to product wastage and reduced consumer satisfaction, impacting brand reputation.    </li>    <li>        <strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong>        Strict regulations concerning food safety and quality can create complexities and added costs for manufacturers. Staying compliant while managing production can be burdensome.    </li>    <li>        <strong>Sustainability Pressures:</strong>        The green movement is prompting producers to reconsider their practices. There is an increasing demand for eco-friendly processes and reduction in waste, which can be difficult to implement.    </li></ul><h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Nuts Huller Market</h2><ul>    <li>        <strong>Technological Advancements:</strong>        The integration of IoT and AI into hulling machines provides opportunities for efficiency improvements. Smart machines can monitor quality in real time, leading to better output and reduced waste.    </li>    <li>        <strong>Rising Health Awareness:</strong>        As consumers become more health-conscious, the demand for nuts as a healthy snack is increasing. This trend opens pathways for market expansion and innovation in product offerings.    </li>    <li>        <strong>Value-Added Products:</st